<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Black Rider Makes Me Squeamish<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.31)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=18610'>Jason "Jacen" Smith</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=18610&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 26, 2005</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> As I’m writing this, the article that Decipher promised on the reprints coming in Black Rider (that was supposed to be posted on Tuesday past) has not been posted at all on their website. So I have decided to make my own which, while probably just as long, is several thousand times more bitter.<br />
Since I frittered away my youth with sitting in the dark and listening to Nirvana, I’m not a terribly upbeat guy. And I’m not really good with the humour either, like that Poteet guy is,  but if you treat all the spelling mistakes like jokes you can be sure to laugh once or twice anyway over the time you might spend reading what follows.<br />
Anyway, in terms of straight reprints, here’s what we’ve got coming in Black Rider so far:<br />
*A Promise<br />
*Betrayal of Isengard<br />
What worries me more however, is the culture-shifted reprints:<br />
*Abiding Evil<br />
*Troop of Uruk-Hai<br />
I’ll do (by “do,” I mean “analyze,” (writing “do” means I’m “hip”)) Abiding Evil first, since it chills me to my very core. It’s stunning proof of the conspiracy theory I’ve been piecing together.<br />
For those of you too young to remember Enduring Evil, here is its text:<br />
Name: Enduring Evil<br />
Cost: 0<br />
Culture: Sauron<br />
Text: Skirmish: Spot X burdens to make a character skirmishing a [sauron] Orc strength –X.<br />
It was printed in 2001 or some time around there.<br />
And now (in 2005!), an indeterminable number of years later, by sheer coincidence there comes along:<br />
Name: Abiding Evil<br />
Cost: 0<br />
Text: Spot X burdens to make a character skirmishing an [Orc(? Is it called Orc culture? Because then the trolls being Orc don’t make much sense, unless trolls are orcs. I heard that from someone once, but I thought they were lying)] Orc strength –X.<br />
It’s the card - same picture, lore, text, cost and everything. All that changes is the minion culture. This has led me to concoct a conspiracy theory.<br />
Conspiracy Theory: Decipher decided to rotate out Fellowship block in Standard at the last minute about two months ago, after Shadows had been printed.<br />
Prior to Shadows, development must have admitted to management that they had completely run out of ideas for new shadow cards: nothing more could be done with the minions cultures that hadn’t been done to death. Damage bonuses, weird assignment things, playing with burdens, and site control were all utilized by just about every culture already.<br />
As a wise man once mumbled: “There’s only so many places you can stick the cheese on the pizza.” <br />
So, hearing about the problems development was having, some brilliant Decipher management guy decided that, to solve this problem, all that had to be done was to find some way to make sure the players couldn’t have their old minion cards, so they would buy the same ones again. Thus, no new cheeseholes would need to be found for their cardboard pizza, and the game plan for Shadows became to nuke all the old minion cultures and stick a new template on them, so that people would have to pay twice for the same gameplay.<br />
And it worked.<br />
They did the same things they’d done before with a new look and a new template. Their evil scheme succeeded perfectly (except for all the people who got mad and quit the game).<br />
Then, some time later, even though their rotation plan had worked beautifully, they decided to rotate out all of Fellowship block (just for fun). Even though with this new rotation scheme they could reprint all the old cards without nuking the old cultures, they’d already nuked them and decided to stick with it (it’s easy).<br />
To summarize: Decipher, when it comes to the LoTR TCG, must be completely out of ideas, or dazzlingly lazy.<br />
Look at the Black Rider version of A Promise:<br />
Text: Same as MoM version.<br />
Cost: Same as MoM version.<br />
Rarity: Same as MoM version.<br />
That’s the new A Promise. Same picture, same text and yeah, I just checked, and it’s the same lore. Tolkien wrote, probably (I haven’t counted), billions of words in The Lord of the Rings, and Decipher is afraid of using them all up.<br />
And it’s rare again. For those of us who traded for 4 or so copies of A Promise back in the days when it was good (when Shire Countryside decks were viable… and not banned), we will now have more if we happen to buy any amount of Black Rider. And if your group of players has hung on this long, while the number of people playing the game kept shrinking (well, they did here anyway), chances are they have all the A Promise they want and/or need.<br />
The other three, that have been revealed so far are pretty much the same, except Betrayal of Isengard has shifted rarity, from rare to uncommon (I already have two, and so far that’s been much more than enough).<br />
So you’ve got old cards, that a lot of people have, filling up a rare slot, times however many rares get reprinted (whether they be “straight” reprints, or “culture-shifted” ones). It means that there are less slots that Decipher has to try to fill up with something new.<br />
I also just looked and Abiding Evil has the same lore as Enduring Evil.<br />
I think it’s pretty clear what’s going on: Decipher has fired their development team and is simply having their one-man (or perhaps woman) art team cut and paste the old cards into new ones.<br />
It’s the most diabolically lazy thing I’ve ever surmised.<br />
That last part isn’t true in any way whatsoever (I don’t think), but I think the part about running out of things to do with the cards as they stand now is true. We’re getting old stuff repackaged and remarketed without being rethought. At very least the last one needs to be applied liberally.<br />
Yeah.<br />
Anyhow, I should have been asleep several days ago. I hope you were entertained or enraged or mildly intellectually intoxicated or whatever, and I hope that sometime Decipher will wake up to what this does to the game. I also hope you enjoyed the spelling-mistake joks (ha ha! So witty).<br />
Remember, I still love LOTR TCG, I just don’t love buying the same crap I’ve already bought to get the new stuff (like that time with the “Reflections” thing. Anyone remember that? Lost some good players with that one). <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=6001&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
